  "prompt": "Why is Google Maps accused of deleting Palestine?",
  "response": "Google Maps has faced accusations of \"deleting Palestine\" due to its portrayal of geographical boundaries and names in the context of the Israeli-Palestinian conflict. Critics argue that the platform does not label the territories recognized as Palestine by many international bodies, including the United Nations, and instead shows them simply as part of Israel or labels them with names that reflect Israeli governance and control.\n\nThe issue centers around how maps represent contested regions and the political implications of those representations. For many Palestinians and their supporters, the omission or misrepresentation of Palestinian territories on Google Maps symbolizes a broader denial of their identity and statehood, while defenders of the service often cite the complexities and sensitivities of political boundaries in the region.\n\nThese accusations reflect deeper political tensions and the symbolic power of maps in shaping perceptions and narratives around land, nationality, and sovereignty. Google has stated that it seeks to provide accurate mapping information, but the interpretation of that information can vary significantly depending on political beliefs and perspectives.",
